reviewText: I liked Valentine's Day, a film "related" to this one so I was very excited when I found out that a New Year film would be made too. I just fell in love with it since the beginning, because it's not only about the holidays, it gives an amazing message to all the people.Full of dreams, and maybe sometimes cheesy, "New Year's Eve" delivers the thing that the movie is made for: light entertainment, but somehow it made my heart melt.The cast was amazing, some plots were strong (Robert DeNiro) and some others weak (Lea Michele/Ashton Kutcher) but the Michelle Pfeiffer story was my favorite one.Anyway, I can't wait to buy this film! If you are reading this review right now go to the movies and watch it, you won't regret. Ignore the professional reviews.

reviewText: I'm a lawyer in Miami. This is a review. I wrote it because I wanted to share my experience of watching this movie. My wife made me watch it. I just gave you a scooch of the experience of watching New Year's Eve, a movie overstuffed with characters who exposite who they are, what they are doing, and their motivations. The result is a sad spectacle of A and B list actors almost painfully going through the motions with stilted dialogue, explaining to the audience at every turn exactly the implications of the plot developments. "We're not sure if we'll be able to fix it." "But we must fix it before midnight!" "We want to have the baby right after midnight so we can get the prize money!" I mean, are you kidding me with this dialogue?To sum up, I really hated this boring and pointless movie and didn't care about what happened to any of the characters at all. There was one short scene in which a woman was mean to an aspiring actress server that was well done. Right after that there's a speech with a woman holding a dog with no less than three continuity errors involving the position of the dog. (My wife pointed this out. I was proud of her. It's the kind of movie where you notice these kinds of things, as they are the most interesting aspects of the movie.)As a sidenote, earlier in the day I watchedWe're the Millers (Blu-ray+DVD+UltraViolet Combo Pack), which was incredibly hilarious and well done. Watch that instead.Another note: whoever was able to assemble this cast deserves some kind of award. A shame they were all squandered. (Caveat: Sofia Vergara is amazing as usual.) It's kind of like one of those yogurt places where you can get all kinds of toppings. Amazing toppings, but the yogurt is actually dog poo. (Spoiler alert: the dog poo is the movie.)

reviewText: "New Years Eve" is the lives of several couples and singles in New York who connect over the course of the holiday. Eventually, they all go to Times Square to see the ball drop at midnight. Hector Elizondo is a repairman who arrives at the last minute to repair the ball. Two young attractives locked in an elevator; a rock-star's ex-girl friend returns for his concert; and a middle-aged spinster quits her job and falls for Zac Efron. Hmmmmm....There's some funny stuff here. But tacky is two pregnant women trying to force/forward their baby's birth to win a $25,000 contest. Tacky. Not funny. It's all wrapped in fluffy, TV-sitcom land. A frail, sickly old man is played by a frail, sickly Robert de Niro. Most excellent is his nurse, played by Halle Berry. The real bonus in "New Years Eve" is the talent, including Michelle Pfeiffer, Alyssa Milano(I didn't see her), Jessica Biel, Penny Marshall, Hilary Swank, Ryan Seacrest, Michael Bloomberg, Matthew Broderick, Jon Bon Jovi, James Belushi, Sarah Jessica Parker, John Lithgow, and a very bored-looking Ashton Kurcher. The funny gag-reel at the end includes the pregnant women giving birth to twins; which are actually two DVD's of "Valentine's Day".
summary: This film is rated PG-13 for profanity.

reviewText: What do you get if you take a whole bunch of mediocre actors, put them in a film -- in reality, a television show parading as a movie -- and add a holiday that's not really a holiday?  Well, "New Year's Eve," of course.There are a couple of actors in this film that I think have talent, but I won't tell you who they are, because I'm such a nice guy that I don't want to insult the others.  But even those that have talent seemed to leave that talent at the door; can you blame them?  Why give any effort when no one else is?  Why not drink some champagne and have a good time?Was I dumb enough to rent this movie, or even dumber by buying it?  Heck no.  It was on HBO or something, and I have free access to premium channels that's just about ready to run out.  So it didn't cost me anything to change to the channel that was showing this "film," minus perhaps a few brain cells.What's the moral of the story?  Well, what do you do if you're at the end of your film career, or perhaps at the beginning, and need some work, any work?  Well, you sign on to "act" in "New Year's Eve" of course.  What could it hurt?  Well, maybe the audience I suppose.
summary: What a waste of a year

reviewText: "New Year's Eve" is the latest release from Director Gary Marshall and writer Katherine Fugate, who also wrote the previously released "Valentine's Day". She seems to have a holiday theme going on here. Although she may have to come up with a new gimmick because this one may have seen its day. Marshall has had his share of smash hits in his long career, like "The Princess Diaries" films, "Runaway Bride" and the big one, "Pretty Woman".  Compared to "Pretty Woman", "New Year's Eve" is an about to be cancelled sitcom."New Year's Eve" takes on eight different stories in the lives of New Yorkers preparing for the 2012 Times Square ball drop. The stories may or may not intertwine. One thing to note about the movie is that they had no problem getting a treasure of recognizable to Oscar winning or deserving actors. For instance, Hilary Swank, Oscar winner twice, plays the ball drop organizer. Halle Berry, another Oscar winner, plays a nurse overlooking a dieing patient played by Robert DeNiro who's won two Oscars himself and probably should have won more. Michelle Pfeiffer, nominated three times for Oscar, plays a timid lady who wants to learn how to live, all in one night.Despite the presence of these fantastic actors, much of the acting and scenes appear to be unprepared or rushed. It was as if they all got their scripts and two days later, filmed it.  Although to be fair, the storylines that involved Swank, Berry and DeNiro were the ones that hit home with me the most.There are poignant moments in "New Year's Eve". There were even a few moments where I was even touched. Some of the elements that a movie about New Year's Eve should have were done well. Say goodbye. Say hello. Live better. Give more. Learn from mistakes. Spend time with loved ones. Although as a comedy, the movie fails badly. The funniest moments of the film were at the conclusion of the movie when they aired a blooper reel during the closing credits.I'm not a big fan of these type movies where they are telling multiple stories and bouncing back and forth. You don't get a true feeling of relation to the characters and it's hard to get into a flow with a story when it's changing every five minutes. Although Robert DeNiro proves that a great actor can hook you in a matter of seconds. Unfortunately, he's one actor and one story in a movie full of dozens of actors and multiple stories."New Year's Eve" does take you right smack dab in the middle of a night in New York City during the ball drop ceremony, which is a cool thing if you've never been, but it has a thrown together feel and it cheapens the movie. The final twenty minutes of the movie were fun, but the movie as a whole was unpolished and disappointing.
summary: OSCAR winning stars and a RAZZY winning screenplay

reviewText: Upon seeing the cast list for this movie, I was interested to see it. It has a cast of top-notch actors, many famous and well-known... such as; Robert De Niro, Michelle Pfiefer, Halle Berry, John Lithgow, Cary Elwes, Ashton Kutcher, etc.  And, the premise seems a good one - the intertwined stories of various couples and individuals at the culmination of year's end.  The acting is very good.  The cinematography, direction, and editing are all good too.  But, he story itself; the script, the dialog, the evolution of the story... this is where the movie fails.  With a wonderful cast and likeable direction, you would expect it to be at least a moderately good movie. But, the core of the movie - the story (script and dialog) - is weak and lifeless. Aside from an enigmatic performance by De Niro as a dying man who wants to see the Times Square ball drop on new year's eve, the story and dialog is completely lifeless and uninteresting. I really wanted to like this movie, because it had the potential to be a quality comedy-drama... but it fails to satisfy because of bad script writing.
summary: Potentially good story... but fails in the telling.

reviewText: In my much younger days in high school and college, I used to think it would be cool to go to Times Square one New Year's Eve to watch the ball drop.  Now that I'm middle-aged...not so much.  Standing in the cold (and maybe rain or snow) for the better part of a day doesn't seem nearly as appealing now--watching the proceedings on television is just fine.The ball drop in New York City is known the world over, and the 2011 film "New Year's Eve" follows several individuals and couples in and near the Big Apple as they approach a new year.  As you would expect in a movie like this, there is a great deal of symbolism--hope and second chances, birth and death, the old looking back and trying to come to terms with regrets from the past, and the young intently focused on the future.The cast is first-rate, with Robert De Niro, Sarah Jessica Parker, Michelle Pfeiffer, and many more big names--Ryan Seacrest and Michael Bloomberg even make cameo appearances.  Even though this is a chick flick that definitely would not normally appeal to someone in my demographic, the stories are passable enough if New Year's Eve has always been one of your favorite holidays and you have always loved the ball drop--and the cinematography of Times Square as midnight approaches is also very well-done.

reviewText: Garry Marshall follows up his last holiday film "Valentine's Day " with "New Year's Eve." It's not an actual sequel like most people thought when it was first announced. You could call it more of a companion piece. They have the same general structure but with different characters.If you haven't seen "New Year's Eve" yet, don't expect too much. It's a nice little movie to watch with your significant other for a date night. If you've already seen it and want to own it for your home entertainment collection, the "New Year's Eve" Blu-ray will satisfy consumers with a good high definition transfer of the film and plenty of extra features.

reviewText: NEW YEAR'S EVE falls into that class of films best labelled 'cute'.  Lots of stories, most of little consequence, an attempt to pull everything together with the premise that new Year's Eve gives everyone a chance to make things different in the following year (the New Year's Resolution carried to the extreme), some funny jokes pushed over the edge toward silly, and a script full of holes.  But the bouncing around from micro story to micro story works OK because it gives the actors involved a chance to come on set for a day or two of work and leave unstressed and financially healthy.  Katherine Fugate wrote the stewed ingredient stories for Garry Marshall to stir, and the list of actors involved is staggering: Michelle Pfeiffer, Zac Efron,  Robert De Niro, Halle Berry, Cary Elwes, Jessica Biel, Seth Meyers , Sarah Paulson, Til Schweiger, Carla Gugino, Katherine Heigl, Jon Bon Jovi, Sofía Vergara, Ashton Kutcher, Lea Michele, Sarah Jessica Parker, Abigail Breslin, Josh Duhamel, Larry Miller, Penny Marshall, Cherry Jones, Hilary Swank, Ludacris, Hector Elizondo, Ryan Seacrest, Matthew Broderick, John Lithgow and more.This is a razzle dazzle movie with some good moments, improbable though they mostly are, and a nice mindless evening to enjoy popcorn.  Enter with low expectations and take it for what it is - entertainment. Grady Harp, May12

reviewText: I mean--I enjoy a good romance, I enjoy a good comedy; HECK, I even enjoy a good holiday movie.  But above all, I enjoy a character with a purpose and a story with meaning--and let's not kid ourselves, it has to feel plausible.This movie had very little depth, and most times, seemed so superficial.  Allow me to elaborate: Two couples competing to have the first baby in the new year; a teenager who disobeys her mother to run about Times Square with her crush, a man who has been waiting AN ENTIRE YEAR to re-meet some lady with whom he shared a moment on NYE 2011, a bitter guy who hates NYE for really no good reason; and so on and so forth.  Seriously, is this how deep our lives get?  Something about this is just too bothersome to me.  Maybe it was the lack of diversity insofar as to whom this movie was targeted--a very middle class to upper middle class, American audience.  Maybe it was because the Ball dropping in Times Square supposedly set the tone for the hopes and dreams of not only everyone in the country but in the world.  It's commercial.  It's materialistic.  It's disingenuously saccharine.  But above all, it's 1-dimensional.  Don't get me wrong, there were some good moments for me--usually the scenes involving Hilary Swank.  But overall, this movie needs to retire with the New Year.But as the title suggests, some people like this sappy, gimmicky stuff.  And that's ok.  I've given "Valentine's Day" a chance.  I gave this a chance.  No more.  I'll stick to "Love Actually."

reviewText: New Year's Eve with a massive line up of household name actors is such a letdown due to the fact they are all playing characters we already know them as, just with different names. Lithgow pretty much just replayed Dr Dick Solomon from 3rd Rock from the Sun.  Lea Michele's character Elise might have well have just been named Rachel as she was exactly the same as that character from Glee, even singing a duet song as Bon Jovi does his side of it in a kitchen miles away while she's stuck in an elevator. If the plot had just said Rachel Berry got a gig to back up Jensen and got stuck in an elevator this could have been an episode of Glee.  Why get Jon Bon Jovi to play a singer?  Gee what a stretch for him.  He's been trying to become an actor for a few decades now, if he can't play anything but a face for the same old same old written female character to fall in love with or a singer, in this case both, then it's time to maybe stick to being in a rock band Jon. Hiegel played the same character we've seen over and over again in her movies since she left Grey's Anatomy. Why not have Jon playing Ashton Kutcher's character or John Lithgow's and have one of them be the singer instead?  Would have provided a bit of an acting challenge for everyone?  Kutcher as the guy who has let himself go by growing a beard and wearing pyjamas outside his apartment is just playing whatever his character's name was who replaced Charlie Sheen in Two and a Half Men which was based on Kelso from That 70s Show to begin with. Ava was just Gloria from Modern Family, complete with the over the top exaggerated mispronunciations of the English language written for Gloria.  I like that character but if I'm watching Sofia Vergara in something that isn't Modern Family I want to believe her next line isn't going to be Jaaaaaaaaaaaaaayyyyyyyyy! I don't understand why any of these actors took these roles, the thing history has taught us, is to cash in on your fame while you've got a huge fan base from your popular TV show and film investors chasing ticket sales are prepared to cast you, play something completely different so when that show ends you aren't typecast.There's some plot spoilers in the rest of this review if you choose to keep reading. The only decent acting was from Abigail Breslin playing the daughter who is the victim of an overprotective paranoid parent played by Sarah Jessica Parker.  However she had a very poor script to follow, it's unlikely in the real world an older teenager so determined to want to spend New Year's Eve with her friends wouldn't argue it a bit more forcibly when you're actually in Manhattan rather than go home and sneak out your bedroom window (where Hollywood style we don't ever have security screens let alone fly screens making this possible) so early in the day you know you're mother will find out anyway. Plus when you see your boyfriend kissing some other girl from your school in a lengthy kiss you'd have to be an absolute idiot to just take them back.  Even if she believed he didn't instigate it, he didn't push the other girl away at any time either.  Parker as the paranoid parent plays that well, but being the one a much younger Josh Duhamel is pushing away beautiful girls his own age throwing themselves at him to see again is a bit of a stretch. Even if you buy that, how did she organise a horse drawn carriage in a few minutes and why even bother before you know if he is even there being that you haven't even left your daughter at least half an hour after the scheduled meeting time.Other than Breslin, surprisingly it was Zac Efron that was one of the only other actors who provided a bit of acting away from his normal role, along with Michelle Pfeiffer who he as a courier decides to help have a sort of midlife crisis revelation and start to live life possibly for her first time ever.  Deniro as a lonely dyeing patient was also good as was Halle Berry as his nurse.  But really everyone else just replayed characters they play in sitcoms making the overall viewing experience very predictable and disappointing. This movie has an opportunity to be something great with the cast that signed on, it's a shame they obviously couldn't afford any decent writers or couldn't be bothered as they knew fans of those celebrities would watch this anyway. Possibly the actors themselves don't have the ability to play anything beyond what they already do. Who knows, give this one a miss!
summary: Poorly Written Script and Casting, Big Name Actors Just Replaying the Characters They Are Famous For From TV

reviewText: Although the critics slammed "New Year's Eve" as one of the worst movies of the year, the audiences felt differently rather enjoying it.  I kind of liked it.  Nice fluff.  It's an ensemble cast set up just like in "Valentine's Day" except this one is on "New Year's Eve".  Some of the pairings include, Sarah Jessica Parker & Abigail Breslin who play Mother and Daughter offering one of the more bouncier & interesting pairings in the film.  Josh Duhamel searches diligently for his soul mate he met & lost one year ago.  Jessica Biel & Seth Meyers play husband and wife in one of the more unnecessary subplots in the film.  Robert DeNiro & Halle Berry manage to bring deep emotion into the lackluster words printed on the script thus making it believable.  Katherine Heigl & Sofia Vergara give us light comic relief in their bits.Despite the critics attacks on the film they do manage to praise one tiny element within each of their scathing reviews.  They loved the Michelle Pfieffer - Zac Efron sequences, more or less calling it the film's saving grace.  I agree.  I could've watched the entire movie with just them and be fine.  If only the entire movie could've surfaced around their characters.  They were the only actors that actually developed and fleshed out the roles they were playing as much as they could.  It ended up being the surprising charm behind the film and thus allowing me to give it one more star necessary just for them.Most of us have guilty pleasures and we want to escape the stresses, depressions and feelings of isolation in our lives and simply escape into a fantasy.  "New Year's Eve" can accomplish that.The film is a completely unrealistic and contrived world, yet it's bright, fun and full of love. There are many out there exhausted with fighting our day to day battles and watching another overblown shoot 'em up movie with no point.  If you get depressed over the holiday season or are completely stressed out and over it all and everyone in it, then I would recommend watching "New Year's Eve" as it is an uplifter despite it being like a gigantic Hallmark card.

reviewText: MOVIE NOTE #15: NEW YEAR'S EVEWhat a really wonderful movie. It has real humor, great complex characters and humongous heart. Don't miss this. Another great script from Katherine Fugate in the same vain as last year's "Valentine's Day" (which she also wrote)- this film has the same concept of 20 characters with 5 story lines that all end up in the same place and crossing each other's paths! Directed by Garry Marshall himself ("Pretty Women", "Valentine's Day", "The Princess Diaries", "Beaches") - the film takes the lives of a depressed and self-deprecating worker (Michelle Pfieffer of `The Fabulous Baker Boys') who is challenged and amazed by a young currier carrier (Zac Efron of `High School Musical') - and - a negatively scarred young comic book illustrator (Ashton Kutcher of `Two and a half Men') and a confident yet fearful background singer (Lea Michele of `Glee') forced to learn about each other in the confines of one space for hours - and - a mother (Sarah Jessica Parker of `Sex In The City') and her daughter (Abigail Breslin of `Kitt Kittridge') learning that although they have each other...they need to expand their own hearts to the opposite sex - and - a first-class Chef (Katherine Heigl of `Roswell', `The Ugly Truth') in a cross romance with a career driven rock star (Jon Bon Jovi of `Ali McBeal')...And - a lonely man (Robert De Niro of `Raging Bull') who's dying is befriended by a sympathetic nurse (Halle Barry of `X-Men', `Monsters Ball') with a major hole in her life - and - two pregnant mothers (Jessica Biel of `The A Team', `7h Heaven' and Sarah Paulson of `Serenity')with their husbands (Seth Meyers of `SNL', Valentine's Day' and Til Schwieger of `The Three Musketeers', Inglorious Bastards') competing for the births of their babies to happen before midnight New Year's Eve - and - a project coordinator of the New York New Year's Eve celebration at times square wh has a morale and social delema working through her job and her heart played by Hilary Swank (`Million Dollar Baby', `Boys Don't Cry') with the confused life of Josh Duhamel (`Transformers')...And - sprinkle in the memorable performances of actors like Cary Elwes , Hector Alizondo, James Belushi Sophia Vergara, John Lithgow, Russel Peters, Larry Miller, Jack McGee, Yeardly Smith, Ludacris and Penny Marshall (Garry's younger sister!) - you a very entertaining movie. You will literally, laugh and cry - sometimes at the same time too! Great family film with a ot of real-life typr situations that make all the characters believable. The best part - you think you know who is going to do what - and then - wrong! Great writer because of a strong story lines and believable characters. 12-2011
summary: Garry Did it Again! Story and Characters First!

reviewText: I hated and loved 2010's "Valentine's Day", Garry Marshall's attempt at "Love Actually". This film had almost two dozen big names, and had stories that I had seen done in countless films before. There was nothing original about it, but it was a pleasant way to spend a few hours. In the end, I did kind of like it. I hated the way that it didn't give its characters enough time to grow into anything more but caricatures, but it made me smile. I enjoyed the ways that the stories came together in the end, I guess you could say.I was hoping that "New Year's Eve", which may as well have been a sequel to "Valentine's Day", having the same filmmakers, and a slew of other big names, would be an improved version of "Valentine's Day". This one had the exact same effect. It had half-stories that felt extremely gimmicky, a cast that was eager to please, but didn't have any place to go, because they weren't given anything interesting to do. I blame Katherine Fugate for doing to this, what she did to "Valentine's Day" a few years ago.I like a GOOD romantic comedy. I can forgive an unrealistic or unoriginal story if the cast is amiable and charming enough, but this one is unforgivable. I had a nice time at the actual movie, because it was pleasant enough for me to temporarily overlook its obvious shortcomings. It threw its two dozen fantastic actors (this time including some Oscar winners such as Hilary Swank, Halle Berry and Robert DeNiro) into trivial scenarios that end up being less than they began, which is saying alot.For examples of why this film is so ridiculous, I will bother to explain some of its idiotic excuses for plotlines. Katherine Heigl plays the scorned woman, who was broken up with by Jon Bon Jovi the previous New Year's. Robert DeNiro is a dying man whose last wish before dying is to see the ball drop in Times Square one last time before he croaks, and Halle Berry is his nurse. "Little Miss Sunshine"`s Abigail Breslin is a rebellious teenager who wants to go to a party, and her mother (Sarah Jessica Parker) won't let her.These stories have been done to death, and the characters are caricatures once again. The festive nature of New Year's makes it watchable, albeit barely. I enjoyed seeing so many actors that I recognized, but they were simply not given enough material to work with, that could have possibly saved this train wreck. For example, I love Sofia Vergara on the television program "Modern Family", because she is absolutely hilarious, making a character that could have been a dry caricature her own, and making her character detailed and exciting. She only brings life to the few scenes that she is given, although she is reduced to a "sidekick" role who doesn't even have her own story line.I was glad to see Lea Michele working in a project that wasn't "Glee", but she has a stupid part in this, playing a background singer (yeah right...) who is stuck in an elevator with Ashton Kutcher, who apparently hates everything about New Year's. I understand the characters in "Valentine's Day" who hated the holiday that the film was celebrating, but come on now. Who hates new year's?While I don't understand how this film's budget was large enough to pay all of its actors, I can tell that the script was probably scribbled down in a few hours. Not very much attention and money was paid to cinematography, and there is an upsetting amount of product placement scattered throughout the film. Like I said, I had a nice time watching this. I thought it was a pleasant way to spend a few hours. But now that it is the new year, it has zero re-watch value. Once I thought about the film that I had seen, I realized how easy it was to hate.Grade: D+
summary: New Year's Eve: A beautiful hot mess

reviewText: This is as calculated and commercial a film as can be imagined. Rredictable from the first instant to the last, it's as shallow and lifeless as they come. At some point, somebody involved must have had an impulse that was sincere and genuine, but there is no shred of authenticity left in this deathly film. New Year's Eve is a pastiche of numerous stories, most of them retreads, acted out by a large cast of celebrities. Only a handful of characters are given the opportunity to become at all "real," and many are just shallow and annoying anyway, so the viewer has little reason to care how the various trivial complications work out (though it's obvious that they will). Anyone looking for genuine human depth in the characters will not find it, though Halle Berry and Hilary Swank do breathe life into their parts. This film it its own kind of pornography. Heaven knows there's nothing remotely sexy about it; it's just that everyone is clearly faking it all the way through in a laughingly obvious way. The soundtrack is equally heavy-handed and obvious. Even viewers who simply want to eyeball the attractive cast members will be disappointed. Everybody's bundled up and hatted or pregnant or in some other way made unglamourous (except K. Heigl in an amazingly slinky dress, but she's such an unbearable, self-absorbed character that there's no appeal). The setting -- New York -- is also presented in a flat, dull, mostly ugly manner. I thought I would enjoy this film -- just looking for a light, charming couple of hours -- but it's such a cynical construction, so utterly heavy-handed and fake, that it made me really depressed. Yeah, the narrator gives us a dumb little lecture at the end about hope or something, but at that point I was sullen and pissed off at Garry Marshall's horrible direction. He, and everyone involved in this piece of crap, should be ashamed of themselves. I hope it lost a load of money, and I advise DVD buyers... not to. If you really enjoy reading greeting cards, maybe...

reviewText: New Year's Eve is a by the book romantic comedy brought to from the same team that made Valentine's Day.  Instead of Los Angeles, the scene is NYC with the plot revolving around the traditional dropping of the ball in Times Square. Director Gary Marshall has assembled another all star cast (including a cameo by his sister Penny who delivers one of the funnier lines in the movie) who mug their way through a drippy plot.  The appeal to act in this film by so many great actors like Robert DeNiro, Hillary Swank, Hallee Berry, Michelle Pfeiffer and the like must be the campy fun they must have had on the set (the closing credits with outtakes and bloopers is funnier than the actual movie).  One example is Matthew Broderick making a brief appearance as a Mr. Bullerton (get it, haha) and hamming his way through his lines as a big muckety muck.  The film could be worse and is a harmless way to spend two hours.

reviewText: To me, this movie is a sequel to Valentine's Day, even though some actors from the first play different characters. This movie is a great romantic love story and just as good as Valentine's Day. It's the perfect movie to end the old year and begin the new. This movie has Halle Berry who plays a nurse named Aimee trying to help a cancer patient on his last day of life. Jessica Biel plays a pregnant woman named Tess trying to have the 1st baby at midnight. Jon Bon Jovi plays a singer named Jensen that tries to win back the love of his life. Abigail Breslin plays Hailey who wants to spend the evening with her boyfriend in Times Square Robert DeNiro's character, Stan is the saddest and wants to see the ball drop one last time. Josh Duhamel plays Sam, a man hoping to meet up with a woman he met on New Year's Eve the year before. Ashton Kutcher plays Randy, a heart-broken man that gets stuck on the elevator with a woman named Elise and begin to fall in love. Hillary Swank plays Claire, Vice-President of the Times Square Alliance that tries to get the ball to drop before midnight. Finally, we have Michelle Pfeiffer who plays Ingrid. Ingrid was my favorite character in the whole movie. She asks Zac Efron's character, Paul to help her complete her New Years resolutions by midnight. (I honestly think the Ingrid/Paul storyline could have been a great movie by itself) I hope everyone had a great year, and can't wait to see what 2012 brings. I would highly recommend NEW YEAR'S EVE!!!

reviewText: From Director Garry Marshall comes almost the same movie as "Valentine's Day" with a huge spoonful of moviestar sugar (Zac Efron, Halle Barry, Jessica Biel, Ashton Kutcher, Katherine Heigl, Jon Bon Jovi, Sophie Vergara, Lea Michele......................just the tip of the iceberg).  Though the differences between "New Year's Eve" and the cloying "Valentine's Day" aren't great they are substantial enough.  While VD dealt solely with romantic love as connectedness NYE opens up the range of things that connect us, from people to brotherhood/ sisterhood to friendships to locales to even work and competitive egos.  And,yes, romantic love is in there too.  Anyone who has seen VD has already essentially seen NYE but NYE is still worth watching for its very warm and even pained humanity and essentially kind heart.  There aren't a lot of movies out there that pull this off.  There are several relational storylines that stand out but, for me, the one that stands out the most sees Paul (Zac Efron), a young and energetic courier about town who has bigger dreams, encounter Ingrid (Michelle Pfeiffer), a homely old maid who has decided that life has passed her by and she wants to do a bunch of things (like a bucket list) all in one day.  She has tickets to a hot concert that she couldn't care less about but would fly Paul to the moon and so she challenges Paul to make her dreams come true (and, no, none of them are sexual at all) all in a day.  Now these dreams are impossible as some of them require intercontinental travle.  Aha, but Paul is a smart one and he finds unexpected ways to make Ingrid's dreams come true.  And she truly lives on that day and Paul's initially selfish goal of doing this for Ingrid (he sees her as a means to an end) morphs into seeing her for her sake.  It was a nice and touching storyline.  One of many.

reviewText: Following the format of intertwining vignettes à la "Love Actually" and last year's "Valentine's Day," Garry Marshall once again has directed a romantic comedy with an ensemble cast of more than a dozen of talented players. Unfortunately, "New Year's Eve," ends up plodding through its 118 minutes without giving any of them a chance to do what they can do.Set in New Year's Eve, New York, the film follows the life of such characters as Claire (Hilary Swank), Vice-President of the Times Square Alliance; a terminally-ill patient Stan (Robert De Niro) who wants to see the ball drop; a hard-working record company secretary Ingrid (Michelle Pfeiffer), who just quit the job; a successful chef Laura (Katherine Heigl) and her ex-boyfriend Jensen (Jon Bon Jovi); and New Year's Eve hating comic book writer Randy (Ashton Kutcher) who is trapped in an elevator with Elise (Lea Michelle), and so on.I can keep on writing the names: Halle Berry, Jessica Biel, Abigail Breslin, Chris "Ludacris" Bridges, Josh Duhamel, Zac Efron, Cary Elwes, Hector Elizondo, Seth Meyers, Alyssa Milano, Sarah Jessica Parker, Til Schweiger and Sofía Vergara, as well as cameos from Matthew Broderick, Common, Carla Gugino, John Lithgow, Larry Miller ... should I continue?Too many characters clutter up the screen and none of them is fleshed out enough. Their stories, not very interesting themselves, are linked to one another in a convoluted way. In "New Year's Eve" there are so many romances going on, but for me the number does not really matter. All I wanted was just a few moving stories, or just one. Perhaps Zac Efron and Michelle Pfeiffer's story has potential for that.

reviewText: ***Includes spoilers***Well, let me just say I'm glad I rented this.  I liked Valentine's Day (and like that film, I was excited at the prospect of seeing so many talents in one film).  I thought this would be just as cute, but it's pretty forgettable, and unrealistic to boot.  All these people could never fly around NYC on New Year's Eve and never get caught in a traffic jam.  Michelle Pfeiffer's character does all those things in one day? How does Sarah Jessica Parker's character change her clothes so fast right after the ball drops...did Clark Kent loan her his telephone booth?????I couldn't really get invested in any of the characters (especially Katherine Heigl's chef, and Ashton Kutcher's bitter illustrator), except perhaps Halle Berry's. It was a nice surprise to see her get all dolled up after her shift as a nurse, to go sit in front of her computer and Skype with her husband who is serving in the Armed Forces.There were some nice moments...one of the pregnant couples finally seeing the big picture after the birth of their son...the daughter helping her father get his dying wish...Josh Duhamel doing a "Planes, Trains, and Automobiles" impression to go see a woman he'd met a year ago, whose name he doesn't even know.Alas, I wanted to like it, but it's already slipping from my memory banks.  It wasn't total garbage, like some other reviewers stated, but to me it's pretty clear that the actors were just phoning it in.  Two stars.
summary: I wanted to like it, but...

reviewText: This movie was recommended to me by family. My 39-year old daughter AND my 18-year old grandson each spoke highly of the film. They each have very different tastes in movies so I was intrigued enough to see the movie. I was not disappointed. Well acted, good story line with a nice blend of mild drama, romance and comedy. We watch several holiday movies every year and I have added this one to our "holiday library."
Title: N/A

reviewText: This movie was just ok...  There were a bunch of big name actors, it was an interesting story line but was missing something that I can't quite put my finger on it.  I would watch it again if it was on TV but I was glad I just rented it.
